/// Hand-computed sentence-splitter fixtures for the 500+ corpus (TTS-06).
///
/// Every `expected` list is hand-computed against the documented algorithm in
/// `lib/core/text/sentence_splitter.dart` BEFORE running the splitter. The
/// discipline is the point: these fixtures lock in the current contract so
/// future edits to the splitter cannot silently regress sentence boundaries
/// (which the reader/TTS highlight pipeline anchors to).
///
/// Categories:
///  - abbreviations: Mr., Mrs., Dr., St., U.S., etc., approx., dept., months
///  - decimals / numerics: "3.14 is pi.", prices, versions
///  - ellipses: "He paused... then spoke." (ellipses NEVER trigger splits)
///  - dialogue: quoted speech, interrogation, nested quotes
///  - em-dashes: em-dash clauses inside a sentence
///  - curly vs straight quotes
///  - Unicode whitespace: NBSP (\u00A0), narrow NBSP (\u202F) — NOTE: the
///    current splitter only consumes ASCII space as inter-sentence whitespace.
///    These fixtures lock in that behavior.
///  - initials: "J. R. R. Tolkien wrote." — single uppercase letter + dot
///  - sentence-final parentheticals
///  - interrobangs / mixed terminals — sequences like `?!`, `!?`. The splitter
///    treats each terminal independently; fixtures reflect that.
///  - real prose from Project Gutenberg (public domain)
///
/// Source attribution format: "PG #<work-id> ch.<n>" for Gutenberg,
/// "synthetic" for constructed edge cases.
library;

class SplitCase {
  final String category;
  final String input;
  final List<String> expected;
  final String source;
  const SplitCase(this.category, this.input, this.expected, this.source);
}

